{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":13672,"record_hash":"sha256:e9853b83a984a66b45eda41417530a62f5d8be144f2a9b62ba8284aedd16a949","timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:02:40.948Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I think the current POC shape is reasonable for local capture, but if we aim at those two future use cases, I’d adjust the mental model a bit:\n\n```text\nSession data should be project-scoped and durable.\nBranches/PRs should point to sessions.\nThe transcript log should remain ordered.\nConsumers should not need to understand Codex/Claude raw JSON.\n```\n\nSo, not:\n\n```text\nbranch owns agent session data\n```\n\nbut:\n\n```text\nproject owns session object\nbranch / PR / commit / GitButler stack references session object\n```\n\n**Why Project-Scoped**\nBranches are too ephemeral. A session can begin before code exists, move across machines, continue under another agent, and later become related to a branch or PR. So I’d store the durable session under a project-level namespace, then attach references elsewhere.\n\nSomething like:\n\n```text\nproject:\n  agent-session:<gitbutler-session-id>:manifest\n  agent-session:<gitbutler-session-id>:records\n  agent-session:<gitbutler-session-id>:record-hashes\n\nbranch/stack/PR:\n  related-agent-sessions = set<gitbutler-session-id>\n```\n\nThat means deleting/renaming a branch does not delete the session history. A PR link can still point at the durable session id.\n\n**Current Transcript Shape**\nRight now we effectively have:\n\n```text\n:transcript = list<TranscriptEnvelope JSON>\n:seen-record-hashes = set<source_record_hash>\n```\n\nThis is good for an append-only event log. It preserves order, dedup works, and it is easy to inspect. For the POC, that is the right kind of boring.\n\nThe thing I would not want long-term is making consumers parse `source_record` to understand the conversation. `source_record` is provider-shaped. It is useful for audit/provenance, but not ideal for handoff or website browsing.\n\nSo future envelopes should probably include more normalized fields:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"record_id\": \"sha256:...\",\n  \"index\": 12,\n  \"timestamp\": \"...\",\n  \"agent\": \"claude\",\n  \"event_kind\": \"message\",\n  \"role\": \"user\",\n  \"content_text\": \"Please implement X...\",\n  \"tool_name\": null,\n  \"tool_input_summary\": null,\n  \"tool_result_summary\": null,\n  \"source_record\": { \"... redacted original provider JSON ...\" }\n}\n```\n\nThat gives us two views:\n\n```text\nnormalized fields -> handoff, UI, search, summaries\nsource_record      -> provenance/debugging/backfill\n```\n\n**Session Handoff**\nFor handoff, the target agent needs a coherent story, not just raw logs. The data should support generating:\n\n```text\nHere is what the user asked for.\nHere is what has been decided.\nHere are constraints and edge cases discussed.\nHere is repo/branch/head context.\nHere is the latest plan.\nHere are unresolved questions.\n```\n\nThat means the stored data probably needs:\n\n```text\nsession manifest:\n  title/summary eventually\n  created_at / updated_at\n  repo identity\n  starting HEAD commit\n  latest known HEAD commit\n  agents/sources involved\n  privacy/redaction policy version\n\nrecord log:\n  ordered normalized conversation/tool events\n\nartifacts later:\n  plan docs\n  summaries\n  patches/diffs maybe\n```\n\nA key point: a “GitButler session id” should probably become independent of provider agent. Today the POC prefix includes `<agent>:<session-key>`, which is fine for capture, but cross-agent continuation wants:\n\n```text\none GitButler session\n  source: claude session id\n  source: codex session id\n  source: openclaw session id\n```\n\nrather than three unrelated session objects.\n\n**PR / Website Browsing**\nFor the PR use case, the website wants a browsable, ordered, redacted view. It needs:\n\n```text\nPR -> related session ids\nsession id -> manifest\nsession id -> ordered records\n```\n\nThe current list shape is good for chronological browsing. But the website should read normalized fields first. Raw provider JSON should be a fallback/details panel, not the primary data model.\n\nAlso: the current namespace is `meta:local:*`, which is intentionally local-only. Anything for website/colleague sharing needs an explicit publish/share step and probably a different namespace or exported artifact. This is important because transcripts can contain secrets, private paths, prompts, credentials, customer names, etc.\n\n**Most Reasonable Data Shape**\nFor the future, I’d aim at this:\n\n```text\nproject-level durable session object\n  manifest: scalar JSON or small scalar keys\n  records: append-only ordered list of normalized envelopes\n  record-hashes: set for dedupe/indexing\n  sources: list/set of provider transcript identities\n\nrelationship indexes\n  branch/stack/PR/commit -> set<session-id>\n```\n\nFor now, I would not rush to implement all of that. But I would keep the current design pointed in that direction.\n\n**Thing You May Not Have Mentioned Yet**\nThe biggest missing concept is privacy tiers:\n\n```text\nlocal raw-ish capture\nshareable redacted session\npublished website view\nhandoff context for another agent\n```\n\nThose are not necessarily the same payload. The local GitMeta capture can be richer. The shared website view should be intentionally redacted and maybe summarized. The handoff context should be optimized for usefulness to an agent, not perfect replay.\n\nSo my take: current POC is fine, but the future shape should make `session` the durable object, make branch/PR attachments references, and promote normalized conversation content to first-class fields rather than relying on provider-shaped `source_record`.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T17:02:40.948Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}